 by bone or air, unlike US.\n8. Less artifacts than CT especially in the posterior fossa of the brain.\nWhat are the regions best imaged with MRI?\n1. Abdomen (to clarify CT or ultrasound findings)\n2. Bile ducts and pancreatic duct (magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography\n[MRCP])\n3. Brain (especially the posterior fossa, nuclei, cranial nerves, and white matter tracts)\n4. Cervical, thoracic, and lumbar spine\n5. Female pelvis (to clarify ultrasound or CT findings)\n6. Joints\nA-Elbow B-Fingers C-Foot and ankle D-Hip E-Knee F-Shoulder\nG-Temporomandibular joint H-Wrist\n7. Staging endometrial cancer\n8. Staging prostate cancer\n9. Vascular structures (magnetic resonance arteriography and venography)\nLimitations of MRI: Safety considerations of MRI:\n▪ MRI costs twice as much as CT and, ▪ Never enter MRI room with anything\n▪ Not appropriate for people with metal that is ferromagnetic.\nimplants (including some ▪ Magnetic strips on credit cards are\npacemakers, artificial joints, and erased by magentic field.\ncochlear implants) because it employs ▪ Pacemakers malfunction, anuerysm\nstrong magnetic waves clips dislodge.\n▪ Claustrophobia. ▪ Remove any metal objects before\nentering the scan room.\n8"}